NOTES:

Stage 1: The First NameSelect from male, female, or neutral arrays based on character metadata.Stage 2: The Primary Surname ConstructionRoll to decide if the surname is Static (picked from the list) or Fused (Prefix + Suffix).70% Static: Pull one from static_last_names.30% Fusion: Combine 1 fusion_prefix + 1 fusion_suffix. (e.g., Grab + puss = Grabpuss).Stage 3: The Complexity Modifier (The "Suffix Roll")Generate a random float $r_1 \in [0, 1]$.If $r_1 \le 0.65$: The name gets a "Dangling Suffix."Pull from fusion_suffixes and append it to the end of whatever was generated in Stage 2.Example: Plowson becomes Plowsonberg.Stage 4: The Hyphenation BranchIf (and only if) Stage 3 triggered (the 65% chance), roll $r_2 \in [0, 1]$.If $r_2 \le 0.50$: The name becomes hyphenated.Run Stage 2 again to generate a second surname.Append it with a hyphen: Plowsonberg-Schleppman.Stage 5: The "Double Suffix" RarityIf Stage 4 triggered, roll $r_3 \in [0, 1]$.If $r_3 \le 0.10$: The second half of the hyphenated name also gets a suffix.Example: Dickard Spankman-Buttsinger.

Since you are fusing words, you’ll occasionally get double letters (e.g., Sack + ker = Sackker). Tell the developer to add a simple regex or string check to collapse triple consonants or fix awkward pairings like "ttb" into "tb" if you want it to look slightly more "natural."

